Inverse Laplace Transform
The Laplace Transform can be inversed, such that \mathscr{L}^{-1}\{ \mathscr{L}\{f(t)\}\} = f(t).
For example, we can say that
\mathscr{L}\{1\} = \frac{1}{s} \to \mathscr{L}^{-1}\{\frac{1}{s}\} = 1
This is pivotal to Solving Linear Differential Equations with Laplace Transforms.
Common Inverse Transforms

\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{\frac{1}{s}\} = 1
\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{\frac{n!}{s^{n+1}}\} = t^{n}
\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{\frac{k}{s^{2}+k^{2}}\} = \sin{(kt)}
\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{\frac{k}{s^{2}-k^{2}}\} = \sinh{(kt)}
\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{\frac{1}{s-a}\} = e^{at}
\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{\frac{s}{s^{2}+k^{2}}\}= \cos{(kt)}
\mathscr{L}^{-1}\{\frac{s}{s^{2}-k^{2}}\} = \cosh{(kt)}

