Concepts/Math/Tensor-Calculus/Metric-Equ.content:
Metric Equation
The metric equation relates infinitesimal changes in Euclidean distance to changes in the Coordinate System. The Differential metric equation is given by
ds^{2} = Z_{ij} dZ^{i} dZ^{j}
where ds^{2} is the infinitesimal Arc Length squared, Z_{ij} is the Metric Tensor, and dZ^{i} and dZ^{j} are small changes in each coordinate axis.
Solving this equation as a Differential Equation for ds yields that the Arc Length L is given by L = \int\limits_{t = a}^{t =b}{\sqrt{Z_{ij} \frac{dZ^{i}}{dt} \frac{dZ^{j}}{dt}}dt}

