Concepts/Science/Physics/Waves/Doppler-E.content:
Doppler Equation
To an observed frequency when the source of the sound is approaching or receding, we will apply the Doppler Equation: f_{o}=\left[\frac{v}{v \pm v_{s}} \right]f_{s}
Where f_{o} is the observed frequency, v is the speed of sound, v_{s} is the speed of the sound’s source, and f_{s} is the frequency emitted by the source of the sound. A plus sign is used when the source is moving away from the observer, and a minus sign is used when the source is moving toward the observer.

Concepts/Science/Physics/Waves/SHM/Reson.content:
Topic: SHM
Resonance
An object has a natural Frequency, at which it undergoes Simple Harmonic Motion. For a Simple Pendulum, this is \omega = \sqrt{\frac{g}{\ell}}. For a Mass On A Spring, this is \omega = \sqrt{\frac{k}{m}}. When an additional driving force is applied to an object, it will be most effective when applied at the same frequency as the natural.  This phenomenon is referred to as resonance.
Mass on a Spring
\sum\limits F = ma = -kx -bv + F_{0} \cos{(\omega t)}
\frac{d^{2}x}{dt^{2}} + \frac{b}{m} \frac{dx}{dt} + kx = F_{0} \cos{(\omega t)}
This is a non-homogenous Differential Equation, which is somewhat difficult to solve, but a solution is:
x(t) = A_{0} \sin{(\omega t + \phi_{0})}
where A_{0} = \frac{F_{0}}{m\sqrt{(\omega^{2} - \omega_{0}^{2}) + \frac{b^{2}\omega^{2}}{m^{2}}}} \quad \text{and} \quad \phi_{0} = \arctan{\left(\frac{\omega_{0}^{2} - \omega^{2}}{\omega\left(\frac{b}{m}\right)}\right)}
See Undetermined Coefficients for Non-Homogeneous ODEs for techniques to solve this.
Q-Value
The width or (q)uality of a resonant peak is often specified by its Q-value:
Q = \frac{m\omega_{0}}{b}
\text{Width of Resonant Peak} = \frac{\text{Mass} \times \text{ Natural Frequency}}{\text{Damping Constant}}

The given images shows how different Q values can impact the behavior of resonance.

