Concepts/Science/Physics/Waves/Wave-Inte.content:
Topic:  Waves
Wave Intensity
The intensity of a wave is defined as the average Power transported across a unit area perpendicular to the direction of Energy flow:
I = \frac{\overline{P}}{\overline{S}} = 2\pi^{2}v\rho f^{2}A^{2}
in units of watts per square meter (\text{W/m}^{2}).
Derivation
The intensity of a wave comes from its energy as seen below:
E = \frac{1}{2}kA^{2}
f = \frac{1}{2\pi} \sqrt{\frac{k}{m}} \to k = 4\pi^{2}f^{2}m
E = 2 \pi^{2} f^{2} m A^{2}
For a simple wave traveling in an elastic medium, it travels a distance of \ell = \lambda f t = vt in time t. The volume of this chunk is V = S \times \ell where S is the cross-sectional area, so m = \rho V = \rho S v t and
E = 2\pi^{2}f^{2}\rho S v t A^{2}
The average rate of energy, or power of the wave, is:
\overline{P} = \frac{E}{t} = 2\pi^{2} f^{2} \rho S v A^{2}
I = \frac{\overline{P}}{\overline{S}} = 2\pi^{2}f^{2}\rho v A^2

